#### Work done by an expanding gas

Consider a gas enclosed in a chamber of cross sectional area \(A\) and fitted with a light frictionless piston.

If the gas expands at constant pressure \(p\), such that the volume changes by an amount \(\Delta V\), the force exerted by the gas on the piston, \(F_{\text{gp}}\), is

\[F_{\text{gp}}=pA\]

and the displacement of the piston, \(\Delta x\), is given by

\[\Delta x=\frac{\Delta V}{A}\]

The work done by the gas on the piston, \(W_{\text{gp}}\), is

\[W_{\text{gp}} =F_{\text{gp}}x\] \[=(pA)(\frac{\Delta V}{A})\]

Hence,

\[W_{\text{gp}}=p\Delta V\]

**Determining work done by gas**

If the pressure is not constant, the work done by the gas is given by:

\[W_{\text{gp}}=\int p\ dV=\text{Area under }p\text{-}V\text{ graph}\]

**Graphical representation**

Graphically, \(W_{\text{gp}}\) is given by the area under the p-V graph.

_Note: as the gas does positive work on the piston in expanding, the atmosphere is doing negative work on the piston._

