### Power

In practical devices, we are often more concerned about the time taken to do a certain amount of work; a device that does too long to do the work required is not very useful to us. Thus it is meaningful to quantify the rate of work done using a physical quantity - **Power**.

**Definition of power**

Symbol: \(P\)

Unit: Watt (\(W\))

Power is defined as the rate at which work is done.

**Note**

For a device in motion, _instantaneous power output_ at any point in time is given by

\[P =\frac{dW}{dt}\] \[=\frac{d(F\text{s})}{dt}\]

If the force \(F\) exerted is constant, e.g. when net force is zero as a constant driving force \(F\) balances resistive forces \(f\),

\[P =F\frac{d\text{s}}{dt}\] \[=F\nu\text{ (since $\nu=\frac{d\text{s}}{dt}$ is velocity)}\]

For a stationary device that does work \(\Delta W\)in a time interval \(t\), the average power is given by

\[\left<P\right>=\frac{\Delta W}{t}\]

